{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Authentication System</h1>
    <p>
        Rhapsody provides a complete, self-contained authentication system built with 
        <strong>Doctrine ORM</strong> and the <code>User</code> entity. It handles 
        registration, login, logout, and password reset flows out of the box.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/40 border-l-4 border-blue-500 dark:border-blue-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300">Important:</strong>
        <p class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300 mt-1">
            The authentication system is <strong>optional</strong>. You are not required to use it. 
            You can build your own authentication system, or extend the built-in one.
        </p>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Installation</h2>
    <p>
        Before using the authentication system, you <strong>must</strong> create the required 
        database tables. Run the following command from your project root:
    </p>
    <pre class="command-line"><code class="language-bash">php rhapsody auth:install</code></pre>
    <p>
        This command creates the <code>users</code> and <code>password_resets</code> tables 
        based on the core <code>User</code> entity definition.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-yellow-50 dark:bg-yellow-950/40 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 dark:border-yellow-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300">⚠️ Important:</strong>
        <p class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300 mt-1">
            Running <code>auth:install</code> is <strong>required</strong> before any authentication 
            routes will work. The command will skip tables that already exist, so it's safe to run 
            multiple times.
        </p>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>How It Works</h2>
    <p>
        The authentication system is self-contained within the core framework:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Controller:</strong> <code>Rhapsody\Core\Controllers\AuthController</code></li>
        <li><strong>Entity:</strong> <code>Rhapsody\Core\Entities\User</code></li>
        <li><strong>Views:</strong> <code>@core/auth/*.twig</code> (login, register, forgot-password, reset-password)</li>
        <li><strong>Routes:</strong> Registered automatically from the core routes file</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        The following routes are available out of the box:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-text">GET  /login              → Show login form
POST /login              → Handle login
GET  /register           → Show registration form
POST /register           → Handle registration
POST /logout             → Log out
GET  /forgot-password    → Show forgot password form
POST /forgot-password    → Send reset link
GET  /reset-password/{token} → Show reset password form
POST /reset-password     → Handle password reset</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Using the Built-in Auth System</h2>
    <p>
        To use the default authentication system, simply ensure the routes are registered 
        (they are automatically loaded from the core) and point your users to <code>/login</code> 
        and <code>/register</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
        In your templates, you can check if a user is logged in using the <code>auth</code> global:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;&#123;% if auth.check %&#125;&#125;
    Welcome back, &#123;&#123; auth.user.name &#125;&#125;!
    &lt;a href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/logout"&gt;Logout&lt;/a&gt;
&#123;&#123;% else %&#125;&#125;
    &lt;a href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/login"&gt;Login&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;a href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/register"&gt;Register&lt;/a&gt;
&#123;&#123;% endif %&#125;&#125;</code></pre>
    <p>
        Protect routes with the <code>auth</code> middleware:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">Router::get('/dashboard', [DashboardController::class, 'index'])->middleware('auth');</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Extending the Built-in Auth System</h2>
    <p>
        If you want to add custom functionality (e.g., additional fields, custom validation, 
        or custom email templates), you can <strong>extend</strong> the core controller:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// app/Controllers/AuthController.php
namespace App\Controllers;

use Rhapsody\Core\Controllers\AuthController as BaseAuthController;
use Rhapsody\Core\Request;
use Rhapsody\Core\Response;

class AuthController extends BaseAuthController
{
    public function showRegisterForm(): Response
    {
        // Add custom data to the registration view
        return $this->view('auth/register.twig', [
            'terms_accepted' => false,
        ]);
    }

    public function register(Request $request): Response
    {
        // Add custom validation before parent registration
        // Or override the entire registration logic
        // return parent::register($request);
    }
}</code></pre>
    <p>
        Then update your <code>routes/web.php</code> to point to your custom controller:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">Router::get('/register', [App\Controllers\AuthController::class, 'showRegisterForm']);
Router::post('/register', [App\Controllers\AuthController::class, 'register']);</code></pre>

    <h3>Extending the User Entity</h3>
    <p>
        To add custom fields to the user (e.g., <code>phone</code>, <code>avatar</code>), you can 
        extend the core entity:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// app/Entities/User.php
namespace App\Entities;

use Doctrine\ORM\Mapping as ORM;
use Rhapsody\Core\Entities\User as BaseUser;

#[ORM\Entity]
#[ORM\Table(name: 'users')]
class User extends BaseUser
{
    #[ORM\Column(type: 'string', nullable: true)]
    private ?string $phone = null;

    public function getPhone(): ?string
    {
        return $this->phone;
    }

    public function setPhone(?string $phone): void
    {
        $this->phone = $phone;
    }
}</code></pre>
    <p>
        <strong>Note:</strong> If you create your own <code>App\Entities\User</code> entity, it will 
        <strong>override</strong> the core <code>User</code> entity. Make sure your entity contains 
        all the fields the auth system expects, or extend the base entity as shown above.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Building Your Own Auth System (Alternative)</h2>
    <p>
        If the built-in authentication system doesn't meet your needs, you can build your own 
        from scratch. This is recommended if you need:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Integration with external authentication providers (LDAP, OAuth)</li>
        <li>Non-email based login (e.g., username only)</li>
        <li>Custom session management</li>
        <li>Different user storage (e.g., Redis, external API)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        To build your own system, you can either:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Create a completely separate auth controller</strong> – 
            Create your own <code>LoginController</code> and <code>RegisterController</code> 
            in <code>app/Controllers/</code> and use your own routes.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Create independent login/register controllers</strong> – 
            This is the recommended approach as it keeps responsibilities separated.
        </li>
    </ol>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// app/Controllers/LoginController.php
namespace App\Controllers;

use Rhapsody\Core\BaseController;
use Rhapsody\Core\Request;
use Rhapsody\Core\Response;
use Rhapsody\Core\Session;

class LoginController extends BaseController
{
    public function showForm(): Response
    {
        return $this->view('auth/custom-login.twig');
    }

    public function login(Request $request): Response
    {
        // Your custom login logic here
        // Validate credentials, set session, etc.
    }

    public function logout(): Response
    {
        Session::destroy();
        return redirect('/login');
    }
}</code></pre>
    <p>
        Then register your routes in <code>routes/web.php</code>:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">Router::get('/login', [LoginController::class, 'showForm']);
Router::post('/login', [LoginController::class, 'login']);
Router::post('/logout', [LoginController::class, 'logout']);</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Customizing Views</h2>
    <p>
        To override the default authentication views, create matching templates in your 
        active theme:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">views/themes/your-theme/auth/login.twig
views/themes/your-theme/auth/register.twig
views/themes/your-theme/auth/forgot-password.twig
views/themes/your-theme/auth/reset-password.twig</code></pre>
    <p>
        The framework will automatically use your theme's templates instead of the core ones if you have set up your own theme; otherwise make sure that your view files extend <code>@core/layouts/main.twig</code>. See the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/themes">themes documentation</a> for more details on using core and custom themes.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Security Features</h2>
    <p>The built-in authentication system includes the following security measures:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Password hashing:</strong> Passwords are hashed using <code>password_hash()</code> with BCRYPT</li>
        <li><strong>CSRF protection:</strong> All forms include a CSRF token field</li>
        <li><strong>Session regeneration:</strong> Session ID is regenerated on login</li>
        <li><strong>Password reset tokens:</strong> Tokens are hashed at rest (SHA-256) and time-limited (60 minutes)</li>
        <li><strong>No user enumeration:</strong> Password reset responses are identical whether or not the email exists</li>
        <li><strong>Single-use tokens:</strong> Reset tokens are deleted after successful use</li>
        <li><strong>Old token invalidation:</strong> Requesting a new reset link invalidates all previous tokens</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

